WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.520
Hi everyone, I'm Christy Heaton and I like making maps with Python.

00:00:09.520 --> 00:00:14.440
So today I'm going to talk about mapping tomorrow's eclipse path with Geopandas and PyScript.

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:19.920
So if you haven't heard, there's a total solar eclipse happening tomorrow, passing over much

00:00:19.920 --> 00:00:23.680
of North America from Mexico up to Eastern Canada.

00:00:23.680 --> 00:00:29.520
So total solar eclipse is when the moon comes directly between the sun and the earth and

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:33.959
casts a shadow where right below where the moon and sun are.

00:00:33.959 --> 00:00:37.000
And if you look at the sun and moon, when this happens, it looks something like this.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:38.080
The skies get dark.

00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:39.959
It's pretty cool.

00:00:39.959 --> 00:00:45.160
2017, there was another total solar eclipse that was much more conveniently located to

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:46.279
Seattle.

00:00:46.279 --> 00:00:51.599
So I went to Oregon and saw the totality and this is me watching the, well, not the totality

00:00:51.599 --> 00:00:55.000
because it's light up, but after it was partial.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:01.360
So let's look at a map made with Python of the eclipse happening tomorrow.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:02.799
Okay.

00:01:02.799 --> 00:01:10.879
So this is a web map, has the total solar eclipse path and it has the cities that are

00:01:10.879 --> 00:01:17.160
going to be covered by the eclipse and the cities are sized dots by population.

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:27.000
So we can see the most populated city, Dallas, Montreal, we got Cleveland, Indianapolis,

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.919
and a bunch of others.

00:01:29.919 --> 00:01:37.199
So let's talk about how I made this.

00:01:37.199 --> 00:01:40.279
So I use Geopandas a lot for spatial data.

00:01:40.279 --> 00:01:43.839
So Geopandas is like spatially enabled pandas.

00:01:43.839 --> 00:01:50.959
It makes it super easy to read in spatial data, make maps with it, do analysis to it,

00:01:50.959 --> 00:01:56.580
and then you also have, like, all the power of pandas to do tabular manipulation.

00:01:56.580 --> 00:02:02.540
So Geopandas is my preferred Python library for working with spatial data in Python.

00:02:02.540 --> 00:02:04.599
And then PyScript is a totally different thing.

00:02:04.599 --> 00:02:06.199
We learned about it yesterday.

00:02:06.199 --> 00:02:09.779
It's a framework for running Python in the browser.

00:02:09.779 --> 00:02:14.559
So watch that talk from yesterday if you missed it, but, yeah, we're going to be making

00:02:14.559 --> 00:02:19.419
this map such that we're going to be running the Python, but you don't have to use any

00:02:19.419 --> 00:02:22.500
local Python installation.

00:02:22.500 --> 00:02:24.500
Okay.

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:26.979
So back to the map.

00:02:26.979 --> 00:02:34.100
So we're here and anyone could go to this link and see the eclipse, and if you go down

00:02:34.100 --> 00:02:40.220
to view code, we can see all the code that I used to make this map.

00:02:40.220 --> 00:02:41.460
So I'm in PyScript.com.

00:02:41.460 --> 00:02:46.139
I really like using PyScript.com to make my PyScript projects because then PyScript.com

00:02:46.139 --> 00:02:48.300
hosts it and I don't have to deal with any of that.

00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:53.580
I just make an account on PyScript.com, make projects in there, I can share the links,

00:02:53.580 --> 00:02:54.979
and that's it.

00:02:54.979 --> 00:03:03.139
So the Python code to make the map is in this main.py file, and you're looking at oops.

00:03:03.139 --> 00:03:06.539
You're looking at all the code.

00:03:06.539 --> 00:03:12.059
So I import Geopandas and some PyScript libraries.

00:03:12.059 --> 00:03:17.259
I already have my data prepared, so I have these cities that were clipped to the eclipse

00:03:17.259 --> 00:03:24.259
path already online, so I can load that in, as well as the eclipse data.

00:03:24.259 --> 00:03:25.259
Same thing.

00:03:25.259 --> 00:03:26.259
I have it prepared.

00:03:26.259 --> 00:03:28.899
I downloaded it from NASA and loading it in.

00:03:29.100 --> 00:03:37.220
These two variables now hold geodata frames representing my data, and Geopandas has this

00:03:37.220 --> 00:03:41.539
explore method, which is like, I mean, you can make a web map with one line of code.

00:03:41.539 --> 00:03:47.300
So you take a geodata frame, run explore method, you can customize how the map looks.

00:03:47.300 --> 00:03:49.860
You don't even have to add any of this stuff.

00:03:49.860 --> 00:03:52.119
There's defaults for everything.

00:03:52.119 --> 00:03:56.580
So you put that in a variable, and then any other layers you want in the map, you set

00:03:56.580 --> 00:03:57.580
them.

00:03:57.580 --> 00:03:59.300
M equals M there.

00:03:59.300 --> 00:04:06.500
And then PyScript has a display method, so this will just put the map on the page.

00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:08.279
And yeah.

00:04:08.279 --> 00:04:10.460
So that's it.

00:04:10.460 --> 00:04:15.779
Another thing I'll mention is PyScript.toml is where you put the packages you want access

00:04:15.779 --> 00:04:16.779
to.

00:04:16.779 --> 00:04:21.299
And caveat that this page takes, like, 30 seconds to two minutes to load, because you're

00:04:21.299 --> 00:04:25.480
not ‑‑ you have to, like, load in all of Python and all of those libraries.

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:28.720
So beware if you go to this link.

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:30.380
Okay.

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:38.119
So tomorrow, here in Seattle, we won't be able to see the total solar eclipse, but we'll

00:04:38.119 --> 00:04:44.320
see a partial eclipse and about 20% totality around late morning.

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:49.519
So if we're ‑‑ we have clear skies, check it out with safety glasses.

00:04:49.519 --> 00:04:50.519
And yeah.

00:04:50.519 --> 00:04:51.519
Enjoy.

00:04:51.519 --> 00:04:52.519
Thanks.

00:04:52.519 --> 00:04:53.519
Hi.

00:04:53.519 --> 00:04:56.519
How's it going?

00:04:56.519 --> 00:05:01.559
I'm here to talk to you about how to do the same thing over and over and over again.

00:05:01.559 --> 00:05:04.880
My name is Jessica, Jessica Garson, most people call me.

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:09.959
I'm on the Internet, most places, at Jessica Garson, and I'm a senior developer advocate

00:05:09.959 --> 00:05:11.480
at Elastic.

00:05:11.480 --> 00:05:19.239
And a big part of my job is making demos and talks and quick kind of fun, engaging, technical

00:05:19.239 --> 00:05:21.559
demos that show you how to do something.

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:27.440
But I keep using kind of the same paradigm for many, many projects where I have to run

00:05:27.440 --> 00:05:30.399
code at a specific time interval.

00:05:30.399 --> 00:05:35.160
And when I first started working at Elastic, I was working with Elasticsearch and my data

00:05:35.160 --> 00:05:40.059
was held in an index and it would very quickly go out of date.

00:05:40.059 --> 00:05:42.079
And you might be wondering, what is an index?

00:05:42.079 --> 00:05:46.480
An index inside of Elasticsearch is a data structure where you can store your data in

00:05:46.480 --> 00:05:48.880
documents.

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:54.839
But I use this paradigm all the time for everything from a Twitter bot that will tweet

00:05:54.839 --> 00:06:02.359
pictures of cats to things for just, like, letting me know when the Celtics are playing.

00:06:02.359 --> 00:06:07.440
I basically run the same sort of paradigm over and over and over again.

00:06:07.440 --> 00:06:14.399
And so I've used everything from Google Cloud Platform, I've used Render, I've used Railway,

00:06:14.399 --> 00:06:16.959
I've used just pure Cron jobs.

00:06:16.959 --> 00:06:19.440
But basically the solution is pretty much the same.

00:06:19.440 --> 00:06:23.720
You create a script for uploading your data, you create a Cloud function, and then you

00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:26.079
use some sort of Cron scheduling service.

00:06:26.079 --> 00:06:30.839
I'm going to show the demo today using Google Cloud Scheduler to update your index at a

00:06:30.839 --> 00:06:33.880
specific time interval of your choosing.

00:06:33.880 --> 00:06:38.079
And I also love space APIs and NASA APIs as well.

00:06:38.079 --> 00:06:45.019
So I love using the NASA's near earth object web service, which is a restful service which

00:06:45.019 --> 00:06:48.519
tells you when asteroids are coming or when they came.

00:06:48.519 --> 00:06:49.519
Which is awesome.

00:06:49.519 --> 00:06:53.079
So let me just show you the code really quickly in GCP.

00:06:53.079 --> 00:06:54.079
And hold on one second.

00:06:54.079 --> 00:06:55.079
Cool.

00:06:55.079 --> 00:06:56.079
Awesome.

00:06:56.079 --> 00:06:57.079
Oh, it's right here.

00:06:57.079 --> 00:06:58.079
Cool.

00:06:58.079 --> 00:06:59.079
Yay.

00:06:59.079 --> 00:07:00.079
Okay.

00:07:00.079 --> 00:07:01.079
Cool.

00:07:01.079 --> 00:07:04.079
So I'm just going to give a really high level overview of the code.

00:07:04.079 --> 00:07:07.359
And you can kind of just store everything inside of Google Cloud Functions, which makes

00:07:07.359 --> 00:07:08.839
it really easy.

00:07:08.839 --> 00:07:13.880
So I connect to Elastic, connect to NASA, create a data frame just because I like having

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:16.179
my data in a modular format.

00:07:16.179 --> 00:07:20.559
From there I can actually convert my data frame into documents.

00:07:20.559 --> 00:07:24.399
And then I can also see the last time that my index was updated just to get the date.

00:07:24.399 --> 00:07:26.899
And then I can update all the new data.

00:07:26.899 --> 00:07:33.559
And I basically will take my local main function and I'll just convert it into a Cloud function.

00:07:33.559 --> 00:07:38.679
And that basically serves the same purpose as a main function would serve as well.

00:07:38.679 --> 00:07:44.100
And you can also load in your requirements.txt file and save all your local variables and

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:45.399
things like that.

00:07:45.399 --> 00:07:50.179
And then you can set it to run on a schedule.

00:07:50.179 --> 00:07:51.179
So I have this.

00:07:51.179 --> 00:07:56.320
You can actually see my cats and my Celtics updates as well.

00:07:56.320 --> 00:07:59.160
But for the NASA data, I can actually set it to run.

00:07:59.160 --> 00:08:03.720
So it runs every morning in my time zone, which is New York, at 8 o'clock.

00:08:03.720 --> 00:08:07.399
And I can force a run right now if I want as well.

00:08:07.399 --> 00:08:08.399
So yeah.

00:08:08.399 --> 00:08:12.640
That's kind of a lot of how I do a lot of my creative posts.

00:08:12.640 --> 00:08:13.920
I've used this paradigm a lot.

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:18.760
So if you want to see a full blog post of this and the code that I used as well, you

00:08:18.760 --> 00:08:20.440
can find it here.

00:08:20.440 --> 00:08:21.600
Thank you so much.

00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:22.600
And I really appreciate you all.

00:08:22.600 --> 00:08:23.600
Thanks a lot.

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:24.600
All right.

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:25.600
Hey, everyone.

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:38.039
My name is Sam Edwards, and I'm here to talk to you about Cordo today.

00:08:38.039 --> 00:08:43.919
So if you haven't heard of Cordo before, Cordo is an open source scientific technical publishing

00:08:43.919 --> 00:08:45.119
system.

00:08:45.119 --> 00:08:49.039
It's really similar to Jupyter Notebooks or R Markdown if you've used those before.

00:08:49.039 --> 00:08:52.559
So I want to give you an overview of what is Cordo and how I use it for reproducible

00:08:52.559 --> 00:08:58.320
reporting.

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:02.239
So we're in VS Code, and there's a Cordo VS Code extension that I can use to preview my

00:09:02.239 --> 00:09:06.359
Cordo documents.

00:09:06.359 --> 00:09:10.799
This is an example of Cordo slides that I'll use to walk through Cordo today.

00:09:10.799 --> 00:09:12.599
So a little bit about me.

00:09:12.599 --> 00:09:14.140
I work at a company called Posit.

00:09:14.140 --> 00:09:17.599
We create open source software for data scientists.

00:09:17.599 --> 00:09:22.200
Some of our most popular stuff that we've created is the RStudio IDE, Shiny for R and

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:25.400
Python, Cordo, and there's lots more stuff that we create as well.

00:09:25.400 --> 00:09:30.919
And again, about Cordo, it's a scientific and technical publishing system, but the simplest

00:09:30.919 --> 00:09:34.159
way to think about it is it's like Jupyter Notebooks, but you can create more beautiful

00:09:34.159 --> 00:09:36.119
outputs.

00:09:36.119 --> 00:09:37.119
So why Cordo?

00:09:37.119 --> 00:09:38.119
There's one tool.

00:09:38.119 --> 00:09:39.119
You can create many different outputs.

00:09:39.119 --> 00:09:41.159
We'll look at a few examples.

00:09:41.159 --> 00:09:44.960
You can author in Jupyter Notebooks or in plain Markdown, whatever you prefer.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.159
I prefer plain Markdown, like you can see on the side here.

00:09:48.159 --> 00:09:51.280
You can have inline Python code, which is one of the killer features for me, and I'll

00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:52.760
show you what that looks like.

00:09:52.760 --> 00:09:55.739
You can create dynamic content, and then you can easily share with others.

00:09:55.739 --> 00:10:01.760
You can publish to Confluence, an HTML page, Deposit Connect, PDFs, Word documents, many

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:06.479
different formats, all from Jupyter Notebooks or Markdown files.

00:10:06.479 --> 00:10:09.440
So here's an example of authoring in Jupyter Notebooks.

00:10:09.440 --> 00:10:12.719
Not sure how well you can see that, but it's just a normal Jupyter Notebook, but we put

00:10:12.719 --> 00:10:17.039
some special syntax here to tell Cordo how to render it, and you can see the output on

00:10:17.039 --> 00:10:19.679
the right-hand side.

00:10:19.679 --> 00:10:22.320
You can create single-page HTML files.

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:27.320
So this was a plain Markdown file, and the output I get is a somewhat interactive HTML

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:28.320
document.

00:10:28.320 --> 00:10:29.320
You can see there's tabs.

00:10:29.320 --> 00:10:31.119
You can see there's embedded links.

00:10:31.119 --> 00:10:34.119
There's interactive plots.

00:10:34.119 --> 00:10:37.320
This is probably my favorite feature, and it's a very small thing, but you can do inline

00:10:37.320 --> 00:10:38.679
Python code.

00:10:38.679 --> 00:10:42.559
So imagine I had some Python code at the top here that created a user object.

00:10:42.559 --> 00:10:46.479
In my Markdown, I can say hello, and then backtick, backtick.

00:10:46.479 --> 00:10:48.960
Anything in here is going to be executed as Python code.

00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:51.479
So I get user.name, and then user.balance.

00:10:51.479 --> 00:10:55.080
I use F strings to format it with a comma, and then the output would be something like

00:10:55.080 --> 00:10:56.080
this.

00:10:56.080 --> 00:10:57.080
Hello, Sam.

00:10:57.080 --> 00:10:58.080
It is nice to meet you.

00:10:58.080 --> 00:11:03.119
So inside your prose, you can embed the output of your Python code.

00:11:03.119 --> 00:11:05.359
You can create emails with Cordo.

00:11:05.359 --> 00:11:10.320
So this is a screenshot from a Gmail email that I sent to myself, and it's just giving

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:15.039
me some reporting on an application I have deployed in Kubernetes.

00:11:15.039 --> 00:11:17.119
You can create dashboards with Cordo.

00:11:17.119 --> 00:11:20.880
So this is just a plain HTML file.

00:11:20.880 --> 00:11:25.440
There's no server on the back end, but what we can do is you can use Cordo syntax and

00:11:25.440 --> 00:11:29.119
plain Markdown to create these really nice interactive outputs.

00:11:29.119 --> 00:11:31.880
You can publish to Confluence.

00:11:31.880 --> 00:11:37.400
And now I want to show you a really quick demo.

00:11:37.400 --> 00:11:47.760
So I have this report here, and let's render the report.

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:51.320
So I run Cordo render.

00:11:51.320 --> 00:11:54.940
It's going to take a few moments, because we're actually going to create many different

00:11:54.940 --> 00:11:57.320
outputs here, all with one document.

00:11:57.320 --> 00:11:58.719
You can see we're creating a PDF.

00:11:58.719 --> 00:12:00.580
We created a Word document.

00:12:00.580 --> 00:12:03.179
Let's take a look at my output here.

00:12:03.179 --> 00:12:05.659
So pause it, connect deployment reports.

00:12:05.659 --> 00:12:07.900
I have a timestamp here.

00:12:07.900 --> 00:12:14.859
If we take a look at how this is generated, this is that inline Python code.

00:12:14.859 --> 00:12:16.780
So here you can see the inline Python code.

00:12:16.780 --> 00:12:19.219
I'm getting the current time, and I'm formatting it.

00:12:19.219 --> 00:12:20.380
I create a plot.

00:12:20.380 --> 00:12:22.260
I have more inline Python code here.

00:12:22.260 --> 00:12:26.700
It's counting the number of items that I've deployed in my Kubernetes cluster here.

00:12:26.700 --> 00:12:29.700
This is a dash plot, so interactive output.

00:12:29.820 --> 00:12:32.020
Again, there's just a plain HTML file.

00:12:32.020 --> 00:12:36.219
There's no server on the back end, so everything's just embedded.

00:12:36.219 --> 00:12:38.340
And then I have another plot here.

00:12:38.340 --> 00:12:40.700
And lastly, I want to identify inactive users.

00:12:40.700 --> 00:12:44.500
So I have this interactive table here, and this is giving me a list of 96 users who are

00:12:44.500 --> 00:12:50.020
no longer using this service, so maybe I should delete them to free up some licenses.

00:12:50.020 --> 00:12:53.059
So this is my favorite format, HTML.

00:12:53.059 --> 00:12:55.580
We can also create PDFs.

00:12:55.580 --> 00:12:58.580
The PDF was created from the exact same code.

00:12:58.580 --> 00:13:00.419
So PDF is embedded here.

00:13:00.419 --> 00:13:04.780
It's not interactive because it's a PDF, but some people like to have PDF outputs for some

00:13:04.780 --> 00:13:05.780
reason still.

00:13:05.780 --> 00:13:08.979
So you can make those people happy.

00:13:08.979 --> 00:13:16.099
I can even have Word documents to make those people who like Word documents happy as well.

00:13:16.099 --> 00:13:24.900
All right, well, I think my time is up, so thank you for learning about Cordo today.

00:13:24.900 --> 00:13:27.739
Hi again.

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:30.020
I'm here to tell you about PyOpenSci.

00:13:30.020 --> 00:13:31.020
Why?

00:13:31.020 --> 00:13:34.900
Because I'm going to be sprinting at it on Monday, and also I think it's really neat

00:13:34.900 --> 00:13:37.900
just to find out about it.

00:13:37.900 --> 00:13:46.820
PyOpenSci is a community built around Python scientific packages.

00:13:46.820 --> 00:13:52.099
It focuses on reviewing key packages for the scientific community and keeping them up to

00:13:52.099 --> 00:13:57.219
date with best practices and also just making sure that the code itself is doing what it

00:13:57.219 --> 00:14:02.859
should in a way that an engineer would be kind of proud of.

00:14:02.859 --> 00:14:05.140
So it focuses on two main areas.

00:14:05.140 --> 00:14:06.140
One is the peer review.

00:14:06.140 --> 00:14:11.539
It has a board of many very talented editors, but they also have a mentorship program where

00:14:11.539 --> 00:14:15.940
they bring in people who have maybe never code reviewed any code anywhere before, and

00:14:15.940 --> 00:14:21.260
they combine these views of the expert and the beginner so that these packages have a

00:14:21.260 --> 00:14:23.820
broad appeal.

00:14:24.059 --> 00:14:30.179
Also if you get reviewed by PyOpenSci, you get free entry into the journal open source

00:14:30.179 --> 00:14:31.179
software.

00:14:31.179 --> 00:14:35.419
Well, not entry, but you pass a review.

00:14:35.419 --> 00:14:38.659
So this is the review guide.

00:14:38.659 --> 00:14:42.219
I have a backwards mouse.

00:14:42.219 --> 00:14:49.659
So there's already many packages reviewed, and there's more up for review, and you can

00:14:49.659 --> 00:14:54.940
submit your own if it's scientifically related.

00:14:54.940 --> 00:14:57.739
But there's also a packaging guide.

00:14:57.739 --> 00:15:02.799
It is geared towards beginners who have never packaged anything, but it really has information

00:15:02.799 --> 00:15:06.739
to guide anyone no matter how many years you've been packaging Python, and I think it's a

00:15:06.739 --> 00:15:11.580
great place to go if you want an opinion on Python packaging no matter what you're actually

00:15:11.580 --> 00:15:14.280
building.

00:15:14.280 --> 00:15:20.960
So that guide is here, and it tries to go through the entire software development life

00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:28.960
cycle not only once, but how do you maintain that and have a package that's healthy and

00:15:28.960 --> 00:15:34.840
has contributors?

00:15:34.840 --> 00:15:42.119
So if you want to come sprint on this, you can join me, and there's a backlog of new

00:15:42.119 --> 00:15:46.799
things to add to the guides, or if you just participate in the guide and tell us what

00:15:46.799 --> 00:15:51.679
went wrong for you, that would be very valuable, or if you want to just come by and say hi

00:15:51.679 --> 00:15:59.719
in our online communities, any of that is totally fine.

